{"title_page": "Bob Hallett", "text_new": "{{notability<!--All claims appear to be inherited notability-->|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| image              = Bob Hallett.jpg<!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Robert (Bob) Hallett<!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1966}}\n| birth_place        = St. John's, Newfoundland\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date)  -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = {{flag|CAN|name=Canadian}}\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Musician, Talent manager, Record producer, Author\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Great Big Sea]] (band member), [[Come From Away]] (music consultant)\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n[[File:Bob -3.jpg|thumb|\nAt rehearsal with the Planks. \n]]\n'''Robert (Bob) Hallett''' (born 1966) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[musician]], author, producer, and entrepreneur, best known as a founding member of the Canadian [[folk rock]] band [[Great Big Sea]] (1993\u20132013). He is also a native of [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's, Newfoundland]], Hallett co-founded Great Big Sea in 1993, with [[Alan Doyle]], [[Sean McCann (musician)|Sean McCann]]<nowiki/>, and [[Darrell Power]]. The band sold over a million and half records around the world, over a twenty-year period. Through his company, Kilbride Music, Hallett has [[Talent manager|managed]] bands and [[Record producer|produced]] records, radio specials, and live concerts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dooley |first=Danette |date=27 Dec 2017 |title=East Coast Music Association (ECMA) still a music industry 'catalyst' after 30 years |url=http://www.lportepilot.ca/news/regional/ecma-still-a-music-industry-catalyst-after-30-years-172976/ |work=[[CBC News]] |location=Canada |access-date= 7 Jan 2018}}</ref> Hallet is a vocal proponent of talent development within the Newfoundland and East Coast Music Industries, and has authored a career guidebook for aspiring musicians.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=19 Apr 2014 |title=Aspiring musicians need to 'work hard,' says Bob Hallett |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/aspiring-musicians-need-to-work-hard-says-bob-hallett-1.2613872 |work= |location= |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"guidebook\">{{cite book |last=Hallett| first=Bob |date=2007 |title= The Art of Managing your career in Music and Sound Recording|url=https://mrsasaki.files.wordpress.com/2014/05/the-art-of-managing-your-career.pdf |location=Canada |publisher=[[HRDC]] - Cultural Human Resources Council of Canada |page= |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref> He works with the producers of the Broadway musical ''[[Come From Away]]'' as a Music Consultant, and has also worked at the [[Stratford Festival]] as a Composer & Music Director. As an author he has written dozens of magazine articles, essays and several books, including the best-selling memoir ''Writing Out The Notes''. He is the owner of Erin's Pub and Tavola Restaurant in downtown St. John's.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} Hallett currently plays accordion and other instruments in the band Kelly Russell and the Planks; he has also been associated with [[The Once]], The Dardanelles, Fabian James, and the Irish Descendants, in various capacities.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Early life and education==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=January 2018}}\n\nHallett attended [[Memorial University of Newfoundland]], where he completed a Bachelor of Arts in English and History in 1989. The other members of ''Great Big Sea'' attended Memorial University at the same time, and together were named Alumni of the Year in 1999. Prior to becoming a full-time musician, Hallett served as Managing Editor of the Newfoundland Herald and as a Communications Officer with Employment and Immigration Canada.\n\n==Career==\n===Great Big Sea===\n\nA founding member of [[Great Big Sea]], Hallett performed vocals, mandolin, mandola, bouzouki, banjo, fiddle, whistles, bagpipes, accordion, and concertina with the band.<ref name=\"ency\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/great-big-sea-emc|title=Great Big Sea |author=Glenn D. Colton|date=March 22, 2015|website=[[Encyclopedia of Music in Canada]]|publisher= [[Historica Canada]]|accessdate=September 1, 2019}}</ref> Hallett, [[Darrell Power]], and [[S\u00e9an McCann (musician)|S\u00e9an McCann]] began playing together in a Celtic band called ''Rankin Street'' in 1989, with [[Alan Doyle]] joining in 1993.<ref name=\"ency\"/> Rankin Street built a following playing at local St. John's pubs, including Bridget's and Greensleeves, and released one recording on [[Compact cassette|cassette]] titled \"Rankin Street\". As Great Big Sea, the group played its first official gig on March 11, 1993, opening for the [[Irish Descendants]] at [[Memorial University of Newfoundland|Memorial University]], and focusing on playing traditional instruments.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} Great Big Sea released nine albums between 1993 and 2010, including several platinum and gold titles. Touring intensively, the band and band members gained acclaim across North America prior to retiring in 2013 following a 20th anniversary tour. Highlights include reaching the top ten of the Canadian [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] pop chart in 1997 with [[The Rough Guide to World Music|\"When I'm Up (I Can't Get Down)]]\", a cover of a song by the British folk group [[Oysterband]];<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.3296&type=1&interval=30&PHPSESSID=l217vq7csbvjmuaq5l1kcq7s56 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-01-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225120456/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.3296&type=1&interval=30&PHPSESSID=l217vq7csbvjmuaq5l1kcq7s56 |archive-date=2013-12-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=50 legendary Canadian songs in honour of Canada's 150th birthday|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3539103/canadian-songs-music-artists-canada-day/|website=Global News|language=en}}</ref> winning the Entertainer of the Year award at the East Coast Music Awards every year between 1996 and 2000;[5] and receiving nominations for several [[Juno Award]]s<ref>{{cite web | title= Juno Awards/Canadian Music Hall of Fame winner and nominations| work=juno-awards.ca|url=http://www.juno-awards.ca|access-date=26 Nov 2006}}</ref> including Group of the Year in 1998, 2005, 2009, and 2011.\n\nSee ''[[Great Big Sea discography]]''.\n\n===[[Come from Away|Come From Away]]===\n\nSince 2015, Hallett has served as the Newfoundland Music Consultant for the [[Tony Award]]-winning Broadway theater production ''[[Come from Away]]''.<ref>\n{{cite news |last= |first= |date=4 Nov 2016 |title=Come From Away goes home to Gander, Nfld. before heading to Broadway |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/theatre-and-performance/come-from-away-goes-home-to-gander-nfld-beforebroadway/article32678264/ |work=The Globe and Mail |location=Gander, Newfoundland, Canada |access-date=8 Jan 2018 }}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://nfldherald.com/bob-hallett-what-dreams-are-made-of/ |title=Bob Hallett: what dreams are made of |last=Pardy-Ghent |first=Pam |date=27 Apr 2017 |website= nfldherald.com|publisher=The Newfoundland Herald |access-date=7 Jan 2018 |quote=}}\n</ref> The show is a [[Musical (theater)|musical]] with [[Book (musical)|book]], music, and lyrics by Irene Sankoff and [[David Hein]]; the ''[[Rock music]]-feel'' of the musical has been attributed to Hallett's contributions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Auerbach |first=Brad |date=12 Jun 2015 |title=Come From Away \u2013 World Premiere at La Jolla Playhouse |url=http://entertainmenttoday.net/theater/16953/2015/06/come-from-away-world-premiere-at-la-jolla-playhouse/ |work=Entertainment Today |location= |access-date=9 Jan 2018 }}</ref> Set in the week following the [[September 11 attacks]], the musical tells the true story of what transpired when 38 planes were ordered to land unexpectedly in the small town of [[Gander, Newfoundland and Labrador]], as part of [[Operation Yellow Ribbon]]. At the [[71st Tony Awards]], the production was nominated for seven awards including [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best Musical]], [[Tony Award for Best Original Score|Best Score]], [[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical|Best Book of a Musical]]<nowiki/>and [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actress in a Musical|Best Featured Actress in a Musical]] for [[Jenn Colella]], ultimately winning for [[Tony Award for Best Direction of a Musical|Best Direction of a Musical]]. In November 2017, plans for a [[Mark Gordon Company]] feature film adaptation were announced.<ref>{{cite news |last=Busch |first=Anita |date=16 Nov 2017 |title=Tony-Winning 'Come From Away' Director Boards Feature Film Adaptation For Mark Gordon Co. |url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/come-from-away-broadway-musical-tony-award-winning-movie-mark-gordon-1202209043/ |work=deadline.com |location= |access-date=9 Jan 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===[[Stratford Festival|Stratford Shakespeare Festival]]===\n\nIn 2015, Hallett served as Musical [[Composer]] and [[Arrangement|Arranger]] for the [[Stratford Festival]] production of Shakespeare's ''[[As You Like It]],'' directed by [[Jillian Keiley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/artslife/1381311-great-big-seas-bob-hallett-finds-new-voice-as-theatrical-composer |title= Great Big Sea's Bob Hallett finds new voice as theatrical composer|last=La Rose |first=Lauren |date=18 Jul 2016 |website= thechronicleherald.ca|publisher=The Canadian Press |access-date=7 Jan 2018 |quote=}}</ref> In this adaptation, the play was set in Newfoundland in the 1980s, and audience members were encouraged to participate in the performance, incorporating props that the audience selected when entering the lobby. All music was composed by Hallett and played by a roots band.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/theatre-and-performance/theatre-reviews/newfoundland-setting-for-stratfords-as-you-like-it-brings-audience-into-the-play/article30327389/|title=Newfoundland setting draws audience into Stratford's As You Like It|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref>\n\n===Author===\n\nHallett is the author of four books.\n*''Writing Out the Notes'', Hallett's reflections on life in the band [[Great Big Sea]] and the [[Music of Canada|Canadian music industry]]\n*''The Ten - Most Decisive Battles on American Soil'' (juvenile [[nonfiction]])\n*''The Ten - Greatest Pop Stars'' (juvenile nonfiction)\n*''The Art of Managing Your Career in Music and Sound Recording''. A guide for musicians and recording artists, this book is part of the online learning curriculum offered by the Cultural Human Resources Council of Canada ([[HRDC]])\n\n===Entrepreneur===\n====Kilbride Music====\nNominated for the [[East Coast Music Association]] ''Manager of the Year'' award in 2015, 2016, and 2017, '''Kilbride Music''' is a [[Talent manager|music management]] and [[Record producer|production]] firm operated by Hallett and business partner Michelle Robertson.<ref>\n{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=28 Jan 2015 |title=ECMA 2015 nominations for 35 N.L. musicians, industry people |url= http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/ecma-2015-nomimations-for-35-n-l-musicians-industry-people-1.2935024|work=[[CBC News]] |location=Canada|access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Local artists leading the ECMA pack|url=http://www.thetelegram.com/living/local-artists-leading-the-ecma-pack-134366/ |work= The Telegram|location=Canada |date=26 Jan 2016 |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= East Coast Music Awards announces 2017 nominations|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/east-coast-music-awards-ecmas-1.3960025 |work=[[CBC News]] |location=Canada |date=31 Jan 2017 |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref>\n\n====Erin's Pub====\nWith Chris Andrews (of the band Shanneyganock), Hallett co-owns ''Erin's Pub'', a traditional Newfoundland bar known as a ''kitchen party'' place. The establishment was the first [[Irish pub]] in Newfoundland, has played a role in launching bands, and was featured in a 2014 [[Cody Westman]] documentary (''That LITTLE Room - The Story Of Erin's Pub'') that aired on all [[Air Canada]] flights in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bailey |first= Sue|date=19 Jan 2015 |title=Erin's Pub chronicled in new documentary |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/erin-s-pub-chronicled-in-new-documentary-1.2917508 |work=[[CBC News]] |location=Newfoundland, Canada |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and Service==\n\nGreat Big Sea won the ''Entertainer of the Year'' award at the [[East Coast Music Awards]] for every year between 1996 and 2000. In 2001, they decided not to submit their name for nomination in order to allow other bands to compete. They were nominated for several [[Juno Award]]s, including Group of the Year.\n\nHallett has served as a Co-Chair and Board Member to the East Coast Music Association and Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ecma.com/news/ecma-appoints-new-board-members |title=ECMA appoints new board members |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=23 Nov 2011 |website=ecma.com |publisher= East Coast Music Awards|access-date= 13 Jan 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n\nIn late 2005, Great Big Sea released its first [[podcast]], with clips of the band bantering back and forth in the studio mixed with various songs by them and other artists.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} The Great Big Sea Song \"Oh Yeah\", written and performed by Doyle, McCann, Hallett, Hawsley Workman, and Jeen O'Brien, was featured in the opening credits of the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] show ''[[Republic of Doyle]]''. Set and filmed in St. John's, Newfoundland, Republic of Doyle launched in 2010 as a new drama, with one of the largest budgets in CBC history.<ref>{{cite news |last=Doyle |first=John |date=1 Jan 2010 |title=Doyle visits the Republic of Doyle |url= https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/doyle-visits-the-republic-of-doyle/article4308605/|work=The Globe and Mail |location=Canada |access-date=13 Jan 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1297754/soundtrack?ref_=tt_trv_snd|title= Republic of Doyle Soundtracks (2010- )|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2018 |website=[[IMDb]] |publisher=IMDb |access-date= 13 Jan 2018|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Hallett successfully campaigned to halt [[Walmart]] sales of [[Saint Patrick's Day]] T-shirts that featured a [[racial slur]] considered offensive to native [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundlanders]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=23 Feb 2016 |title=Walmart pulls 'Newfie' T-shirts |url=http://www.thetelegram.com/news/local/walmart-pulls-newfie-t-shirts-126557/ |work= The Telegram|location=Newfoundland, Canada |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Craig |date=2 Jun 2017 |title=Has a Canadian Slur Lost Its Sting? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/02/world/canada/has-a-canadian-slur-lost-its-sting.html |work=The New York Times |location= |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.bobhallett.com\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hallett, Bob}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Newfoundland and Labrador]]\n[[Category:Canadian folk musicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Canadian writers about music]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador]]\n[[Category:Writers from St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador]]\n", "text_old": "{{notability<!--All claims appear to be inherited notability-->|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name -->\n| image              = Bob Hallett.jpg<!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Robert (Bob) Hallett<!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1966}}\n| birth_place        = St. John's, Newfoundland\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date)  -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = {{flag|CAN|name=Canadian}}\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Musician, Talent manager, Record producer, Author\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Great Big Sea]] (band member), [[Come From Away]] (music consultant)\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n[[File:Bob -3.jpg|thumb|\nAt rehearsal with the Planks. \n]]\n'''Robert (Bob) Hallett''' (born 1966) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[musician]], author, producer, and entrepreneur, best known as a founding member of the Canadian [[folk rock]] band [[Great Big Sea]] (1993\u20132013). He is also a native of [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's, Newfoundland]], Hallett co-founded Great Big Sea in 1993, with [[Alan Doyle]], [[Sean McCann (musician)|Sean McCann]]<nowiki/>, and [[Darrell Power]]. The band sold over a million and half records around the world, over a twenty-year period. Through his company, Kilbride Music, Hallett has [[Talent manager|managed]] bands and [[Record producer|produced]] records, radio specials, and live concerts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dooley |first=Danette |date=27 Dec 2017 |title=East Coast Music Association (ECMA) still a music industry 'catalyst' after 30 years |url=http://www.lportepilot.ca/news/regional/ecma-still-a-music-industry-catalyst-after-30-years-172976/ |work=[[CBC News]] |location=Canada |access-date= 7 Jan 2018}}</ref> Hallet is a vocal proponent of talent development within the Newfoundland and East Coast Music Industries, and has authored a career guidebook for aspiring musicians.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=19 Apr 2014 |title=Aspiring musicians need to 'work hard,' says Bob Hallett |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/aspiring-musicians-need-to-work-hard-says-bob-hallett-1.2613872 |work= |location= |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"guidebook\">{{cite book |last=Hallett| first=Bob |date=2007 |title= The Art of Managing your career in Music and Sound Recording|url=https://mrsasaki.files.wordpress.com/2014/05/the-art-of-managing-your-career.pdf |location=Canada |publisher=[[HRDC]] - Cultural Human Resources Council of Canada |page= |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref> He works with the producers of the Broadway musical ''[[Come From Away]]'' as a Music Consultant, and has also worked at the [[Stratford Festival]] as a Composer & Music Director. As an author he has written dozens of magazine articles, essays and several books, including the best-selling memoir ''Writing Out The Notes''. He is the owner of Erin's Pub and Tavola Restaurant in downtown St. John's.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} Hallett currently plays accordion and other instruments in the band Kelly Russell and the Planks; he has also been associated with [[The Once]], The Dardanelles, Fabian James, and the Irish Descendants, in various capacities.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Early life and education==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=January 2018}}\n\nHallett attended [[Memorial University of Newfoundland]], where he completed a Bachelor of Arts in English and History in 1989. The other members of ''Great Big Sea'' attended Memorial University at the same time, and together were named Alumni of the Year in 1999. Prior to becoming a full-time musician, Hallett served as Managing Editor of the Newfoundland Herald and as a Communications Officer with Employment and Immigration Canada.\n\n==Career==\n===Great Big Sea===\n\nA founding member of [[Great Big Sea]], Hallett performed vocals, mandolin, mandola, bouzouki, banjo, fiddle, whistles, bagpipes, accordion, and concertina with the band.<ref name=\"ency\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/great-big-sea-emc|title=Great Big Sea |author=Glenn D. Colton|date=March 22, 2015|website=[[Encyclopedia of Music in Canada]]|publisher= [[Historica Canada]]|accessdate=September 1, 2019}}</ref> Hallett, [[Darrell Power]], and [[S\u00e9an McCann (musician)|S\u00e9an McCann]] began playing together in a Celtic band called ''Rankin Street'' in 1989, with [[Alan Doyle]] joining in 1993.<ref name=\"ency\"/> Rankin Street built a following playing at local St. John's pubs, including Bridget's and Greensleeves, and released one recording on [[Compact cassette|cassette]] titled \"Rankin Street\". As Great Big Sea, the group played its first official gig on March 11, 1993, opening for the [[Irish Descendants]] at [[Memorial University of Newfoundland|Memorial University]], and focusing on playing traditional instruments.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} Great Big Sea released nine albums between 1993 and 2010, including several platinum and gold titles. Touring intensively, the band and band members gained acclaim across North America prior to retiring in 2013 following a 20th anniversary tour. Highlights include reaching the top ten of the Canadian [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] pop chart in 1997 with [[The Rough Guide to World Music|\"When I'm Up (I Can't Get Down)]]\", a cover of a song by the British folk group [[Oysterband]];<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.3296&type=1&interval=30&PHPSESSID=l217vq7csbvjmuaq5l1kcq7s56 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-01-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225120456/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.3296&type=1&interval=30&PHPSESSID=l217vq7csbvjmuaq5l1kcq7s56 |archive-date=2013-12-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=50 legendary Canadian songs in honour of Canada's 150th birthday|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3539103/canadian-songs-music-artists-canada-day/|website=Global News|language=en}}</ref> winning the Entertainer of the Year award at the East Coast Music Awards every year between 1996 and 2000;[5] and receiving nominations for several [[Juno Award]]s<ref>{{cite web | title= Juno Awards/Canadian Music Hall of Fame winner and nominations| work=juno-awards.ca|url=http://www.juno-awards.ca|access-date=26 Nov 2006}}</ref> including Group of the Year in 1998, 2005, 2009, and 2011.\n\nSee ''[[Great Big Sea discography]]''.\n\n===[[Come from Away|Come From Away]]===\n\nSince 2015, Hallett has served as the Newfoundland Music Consultant for the [[Tony Award]]-winning Broadway theater production ''[[Come from Away]]''.<ref>\n{{cite news |last= |first= |date=4 Nov 2016 |title=Come From Away goes home to Gander, Nfld. before heading to Broadway |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/theatre-and-performance/come-from-away-goes-home-to-gander-nfld-beforebroadway/article32678264/ |work=The Globe and Mail |location=Gander, Newfoundland, Canada |access-date=8 Jan 2018 }}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://nfldherald.com/bob-hallett-what-dreams-are-made-of/ |title=Bob Hallett: what dreams are made of |last=Pardy-Ghent |first=Pam |date=27 Apr 2017 |website= nfldherald.com|publisher=The Newfoundland Herald |access-date=7 Jan 2018 |quote=}}\n</ref> The show is a [[Musical (theater)|musical]] with [[Book (musical)|book]], music, and lyrics by Irene Sankoff and [[David Hein]]; the ''[[Rock music]]-feel'' of the musical has been attributed to Hallett's contributions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Auerbach |first=Brad |date=12 Jun 2015 |title=Come From Away \u2013 World Premiere at La Jolla Playhouse |url=http://entertainmenttoday.net/theater/16953/2015/06/come-from-away-world-premiere-at-la-jolla-playhouse/ |work=Entertainment Today |location= |access-date=9 Jan 2018 }}</ref> Set in the week following the [[September 11 attacks]], the musical tells the true story of what transpired when 38 planes were ordered to land unexpectedly in the small town of [[Gander, Newfoundland and Labrador]], as part of [[Operation Yellow Ribbon]]. At the [[71st Tony Awards]], the production was nominated for seven awards including [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best Musical]], [[Tony Award for Best Original Score|Best Score]], [[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical|Best Book of a Musical]]<nowiki/>and [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actress in a Musical|Best Featured Actress in a Musical]] for [[Jenn Colella]], ultimately winning for [[Tony Award for Best Direction of a Musical|Best Direction of a Musical]]. In November 2017, plans for a [[Mark Gordon Company]] feature film adaptation were announced.<ref>{{cite news |last=Busch |first=Anita |date=16 Nov 2017 |title=Tony-Winning 'Come From Away' Director Boards Feature Film Adaptation For Mark Gordon Co. |url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/come-from-away-broadway-musical-tony-award-winning-movie-mark-gordon-1202209043/ |work=deadline.com |location= |access-date=9 Jan 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===[[Stratford Festival|Stratford Shakespeare Festival]]===\n\nIn 2015, Hallett served as Musical [[Composer]] and [[Arrangement|Arranger]] for the [[Stratford Festival]] production of Shakespeare's ''[[As You Like It]],'' directed by [[Jillian Keiley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/artslife/1381311-great-big-seas-bob-hallett-finds-new-voice-as-theatrical-composer |title= Great Big Sea's Bob Hallett finds new voice as theatrical composer|last=La Rose |first=Lauren |date=18 Jul 2016 |website= thechronicleherald.ca|publisher=The Canadian Press |access-date=7 Jan 2018 |quote=}}</ref> In this adaptation, the play was set in Newfoundland in the 1980s, and audience members were encouraged to participate in the performance, incorporating props that the audience selected when entering the lobby. All music was composed by Hallett and played by a roots band.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/theatre-and-performance/theatre-reviews/newfoundland-setting-for-stratfords-as-you-like-it-brings-audience-into-the-play/article30327389/|title=Newfoundland setting draws audience into Stratford's As You Like It|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref>\n\n===Author===\n\nHallett is the author of four books.\n*''Writing Out the Notes'', Hallett's reflections on life in the band [[Great Big Sea]] and the [[Music of Canada|Canadian music industry]]\n*''The Ten - Most Decisive Battles on American Soil'' (juvenile [[nonfiction]])\n*''The Ten - Greatest Pop Stars'' (juvenile nonfiction)\n*''The Art of Managing Your Career in Music and Sound Recording''. A guide for musicians and recording artists, this book is part of the online learning curriculum offered by the Cultural Human Resources Council of Canada ([[HRDC]])\n\n===Entrepreneur===\n====Kilbride Music====\nNominated for the [[East Coast Music Association]] ''Manager of the Year'' award in 2015, 2016, and 2017, '''Kilbride Music''' is a [[Talent manager|music management]] and [[Record producer|production]] firm operated by Hallett and business partner Michelle Robertson.<ref>\n{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=28 Jan 2015 |title=ECMA 2015 nominations for 35 N.L. musicians, industry people |url= http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/ecma-2015-nomimations-for-35-n-l-musicians-industry-people-1.2935024|work=[[CBC News]] |location=Canada|access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Local artists leading the ECMA pack|url=http://www.thetelegram.com/living/local-artists-leading-the-ecma-pack-134366/ |work= The Telegram|location=Canada |date=26 Jan 2016 |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= East Coast Music Awards announces 2017 nominations|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/east-coast-music-awards-ecmas-1.3960025 |work=[[CBC News]] |location=Canada |date=31 Jan 2017 |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref>\n\n====Erin's Pub====\nWith Chris Andrews (of the band Shanneyganock), Hallett co-owns ''Erin's Pub'', a traditional Newfoundland bar known as a ''kitchen party'' place. The establishment was the first [[Irish pub]] in Newfoundland, has played a role in launching bands, and was featured in a 2014 [[Cody Westman]] documentary (''That LITTLE Room - The Story Of Erin's Pub'') that aired on all [[Air Canada]] flights in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bailey |first= Sue|date=19 Jan 2015 |title=Erin's Pub chronicled in new documentary |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/erin-s-pub-chronicled-in-new-documentary-1.2917508 |work=[[CBC News]] |location=Newfoundland, Canada |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and Service==\n\nGreat Big Sea won the ''Entertainer of the Year'' award at the [[East Coast Music Awards]] for every year between 1996 and 2000. In 2001, they decided not to submit their name for nomination in order to allow other bands to compete. They were nominated for several [[Juno Award]]s, including Group of the Year.\n\nHallett has served as a Co-Chair and Board Member to the East Coast Music Association and Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ecma.com/news/ecma-appoints-new-board-members |title=ECMA appoints new board members |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=23 Nov 2011 |website=ecma.com |publisher= East Coast Music Awards|access-date= 13 Jan 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n\nIn late 2005, Great Big Sea released its first [[podcast]], with clips of the band bantering back and forth in the studio mixed with various songs by them and other artists.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} The Great Big Sea Song \"Oh Yeah\", written and performed by Doyle, McCann, Hallett, Hawsley Workman, and Jeen O'Brien, was featured in the opening credits of the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] show ''[[Republic of Doyle]]''. Set and filmed in St. John's, Newfoundland, Republic of Doyle launched in 2010 as a new drama, with one of the largest budgets in CBC history.<ref>{{cite news |last=Doyle |first=John |date=1 Jan 2010 |title=Doyle visits the Republic of Doyle |url= https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/doyle-visits-the-republic-of-doyle/article4308605/|work=The Globe and Mail |location=Canada |access-date=13 Jan 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1297754/soundtrack?ref_=tt_trv_snd|title= Republic of Doyle Soundtracks (2010- )|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2018 |website=[[IMDb]] |publisher=IMDb |access-date= 13 Jan 2018|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Hallett successfully campaigned to halt [[Walmart]] sales of [[Saint Patrick's Day]] T-shirts that featured a [[racial slur]] considered offensive to native [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundlanders]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=23 Feb 2016 |title=Walmart pulls 'Newfie' T-shirts |url=http://www.thetelegram.com/news/local/walmart-pulls-newfie-t-shirts-126557/ |work= The Telegram|location=Newfoundland, Canada |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Craig |date=2 Jun 2017 |title=Has a Canadian Slur Lost Its Sting? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/02/world/canada/has-a-canadian-slur-lost-its-sting.html |work=The New York Times |location= |access-date=7 Jan 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references 